From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000008 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: NixOS module overlay <noreply@example.com>
Date: Wed, 8 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 8/8] Don't request STANDARD_IA storage class for fulltext puts

Zotero_FullText::indexItem requests AWS S3's STANDARD_IA (Infrequent
Access) storage class for any gzipped fulltext payload >= 75 KB:

    'StorageClass' => strlen($json) < self::$minFileSizeStandardIA
        ? 'STANDARD'
        : 'STANDARD_IA'

This is a cost-optimization for the hosted zotero.org backend (cheaper
S3 tier for less-frequently-accessed content). It is silently fatal
against minio: minio supports the S3 putObject API with StorageClass
but only accepts a small set of valid values, none of which are
STANDARD_IA. The PutObject call returns:

    Invalid storage class

…which surfaces as a generic AWS SDK exception. The exception bubbles
up through Zotero_FullText::indexItem to the catch block in
updateMultipleFromJSON, which rolls back the MySQL itemFulltext write
and reports the failure to the client. The desktop client surfaces
this as "ZoteroObjectUploadError: An error occurred" with no detail.

Failure is content-size-dependent: any item whose extracted PDF text,
gzipped, exceeds ~75 KB triggers the bug. Smaller items go through
the STANDARD branch and succeed, which makes the bug look intermittent.

Drop the StorageClass parameter entirely and let the backend pick its
default (which on minio is the only valid option anyway). For
self-hosted deployments the cost-tier optimization is meaningless.
---
diff --git a/model/FullText.inc.php b/model/FullText.inc.php
index 1234567..89abcde 100644
--- a/model/FullText.inc.php
+++ b/model/FullText.inc.php
@@ -79,7 +79,10 @@
 			'Key' => $libraryID . "/" . $key,
 			'Body' => $json,
 			'ContentType' => 'application/gzip',
-			'StorageClass' => strlen($json) < self::$minFileSizeStandardIA ? 'STANDARD' : 'STANDARD_IA'
+			// Self-hosted: don't request StorageClass. minio rejects
+			// STANDARD_IA with 'Invalid storage class' for any fulltext
+			// payload over ~75 KB gzipped, silently breaking fulltext
+			// sync for non-trivial PDFs.
 		]);
 		StatsD::timing("s3.fulltext.put", (microtime(true) - $start) * 1000);

